05395nam a22007095i 9783111156552DE-B159720240306014423.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20232023gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831111565527 a10.1515/97831111565522doi  a(DE-B1597)644715  a(OCoLC)1415892212  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE04a361.95611 aAlkan, Hilal, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWelfare as Gift :bLocal Charity, Politics of Redistribution, and Religion in Turkey /cHilal Alkan. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (XIV, 162 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aZMO-Studien : Studien des Leibniz-Zentrum Moderner Orient ;v4600tFrontmatter -- tContent -- tAcknowledgements -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- t1 Fields and Methods -- t2 Waqf as Institution and Imaginary -- t3 Hizmet: A Contested Ethos of Service -- t4 "Our Poor": Criteria, Entitlement, and Justice -- t5 Embodied Ethics of Being a Vakıfçı -- tEpilogue -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aThe welfare regime in Turkey has been undergoing a radical transformation since the early 2000s. Welfare provisions, especially poverty alleviation schemes, are increasingly framed as gifts, and select civil society organisations have assumed the state's welfare provision functions through non-transparent public funding. Waqf, the Islamic institution of endowment, has played an important role in this transformation. It provides both the institutional frame of operations and the religious imaginary signification that interpellates subjects to take part as givers and receivers of gifts. This material exchange of care and money through newly configured gift-relations between the providers and beneficiaries constitutes not only a realm of politics but also a site of ethical negotiations with embodied consequences. This book is based on an extensive ethnographic study conducted between 2008-2009 among the charitable organizations of Kayseri, a central Anatolian city with booming industry and a majority conservative political orientation. A stronghold of the Justice and Development Party (AKP), which has been in power in Turkey since 2002, the city has showcased the tenets of the welfare transformation that is to come, even in the early stages of AKP rule. With a focus on the daily practices within the field of beneficence, the book investigates the gift circuits that bring together central state institutions, municipalities, local notables and business people, religious groups, volunteers and employers of charitable organisations, and the urban poor. In these gift circuits, objects, money, services, prayers, recognition, and political and social influence flow in various directions through formal and informal routes. The book illustrates the growing significance of these particular forms of gift-giving in the field of poverty alleviation and welfare provision in Turkey and their role in the drastic political transformation of the country.  aIssued also in print.  afunded by Leibniz-Zentrum Moderner Orient  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aIslam. 4aIslamische Staaten. 4aNaher Osten. 4aTransnationalität.  aNeoliberalism.  aSocial assistence.  aTurkey.  aWelfare.2 aLeibniz-Zentrum Moderner Orientefunder.4fnd4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/fnd08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe